Armenian string cheese: a denser, braided mozzarella studded with Nigella seed, also known as "seed of blessing." Nigella seed originates from the South Asian flowering plant, Nigella sativa, and is nutty and onion-y in flavor. This nuanced HOUSEMADE fresh cheese will be featured in the main course in the next Cheese in the City Supper. Here!

caption:
Here's your morning #cheese #meditation. A close up of beautiful yellow golden hues. This warm color is reflective of milk quality: the sheep and cows graze on lush grasses and dried hay, which in turn makes the cheese paste have a richer and deeper flavor. 
Featured in photo: Queso Invierno from Vermont Shepherd.

Afternoon tea and snacks at "The Automat." Now, if only every day in Manhattan were like a Richard Estes painting. #richardestes #modernmonday #foodisart #nycxdesign #nycdesign2015 #foodpaintings #vscocam

Morning #cheese #meditation. Aged at @crownfinishcaves in Brooklyn, this cheese is inspired by traditional Italian aged provolone.  Its recipe is similar to Caciocavallo, a stretched curd that is hung two by two over rods. The cheese is rubbed with olive oil during the aging process. We love its bulbous shape.

Featured in photo: Suffolk Punch by Parish Hill Creamery in Vermont. #cheesemeditation

caption: Memorial Day Morning Fontina Cheese Souffl√©. Bright, light, and fluffy. Fontina, an Italian cow milk cheese, is traditionally aged in grottos in the ground, so it holds a special place in our heart. Our mission here is to create and build grottos for every cheese lover out there. We hope you appreciate the little things today. How lucky we all are to be able to share food and drink, living in a moment of peace on this wild planet.

Cabricharme is a goat milk cheese produced in the Southeastern region of Belgium. For six weeks, the cheese is washed in a brine solution, giving it an orange hue. The flavor is meaty and mushroom-y. Here's your morning #cheesemeditation. Enjoy it smeared on toast paired with a smoky black tea. #fravorites

Well, good morning toasted bagel with cream cheese and bacon-strawberry-onion jam. It's so nice to see you. Top it off with some basil for an herbaceous kick. Attn: this is very gluttonous.
Recipe:
Chop 1/2 pound bacon into 1/2 inch strips, fry, and set aside. 
In a large saucepan cook 1/2 chopped white onion, 1.5 cups chopped strawberries, 1 tablespoon apple cider vinegar, 1/4 cup dark brown sugar, 1/4 cup  white sugar, and bacon. Reduce until thickened and jam like consistency, anywhere from 30 minutes to one hour. Let cool, smear on toast, garnish with basil. Enjoy!

caption:
So, today is the day of the bacon-strawberry-onion jam. If you thought we'd stop at breakfast, you thought wrong. Here's a #grilledcheese filled to the brim with burrata and slathered with our precious concoction...
Recipe:
Chop 1/2 pound bacon in 1/2 inch strips, fry, and set aside. 
In a large sauce pan, cook 1/2 chopped white onion, 1.5 cups strawberries (washed, trimmed, chopped), 1 tablespoon apple cider vinegar, 1/4 cup dark brown sugar, 1/4 cup white sugar, and all the bacon. Bring to a boil and then simmer until reduced to a thick consistency: anywhere between 30 minutes and 1 hour. Remove from heat and cool. Enjoy!

caption: Monday morning #cheesemeditation. Here's an unctuous and ripe Mothais Sur Feuille: a goat‚Äôs milk bloomy rind from Poitou-Charentes in western France.  The cheese is wrapped with on chestnut leaf. At this stage, it is perfect for slathering on a piece of baguette. Delicate, buttery, vegetal! Purchased @bedfordcheeseshop.

#cheesemeditation. Zooming in on Mimolette slices. This #cheese is so resilient, we've had it sitting in a grotto on the counter for over a month and a half. Still going strong! Texturally it is inspiring, especially under the light. Right now, we're perfecting our Mimolette chewy caramel recipe. What would you do with this cheese?

caption: Grillin' grillin' grillin' nectarines, goat cheese and peppermint. The saga continues

We've been having leaf wrapped cheeses on the mind; refining recipes for discs of fresh chevre placed in a leafy package and stored in the grotto over a few weeks time frame. 
@sarahecrowder visited @formaggio_essex today and spotted one of our Italian faves front and center: goat cheese wrapped in cabbage leaves, aka Robiola Incavolata.

CG's photographer @sarahecrowder is having an amazing Saturday filled with #robiola #cheese. Here's a snap of her light lunch with Robiola D'Alba al Tartufo from @formaggio_essex . The region of Alba, Italy and the word "truffle" go hand in hand.

Happy father's day! One of our favorite  summer breakfast/brunch ideas on the grill is bell peppers with an egg inside, cooked to runny perfection and then sprinkled with hot sauce and goat cheese. Try it for your pops!

As the days get warmer, we wanna eat fresher. Here's an Hawaiian poke brown rice bowl #topped with raw salmon, cucumber, avocado, mango, and you guessed it...goat cheese! Dressed with a ginger/shallot/hot sauce vinaigrette with black sesame seeds. #ontheblog soon!

This simple salad is an all time favorite.  1/4 of a watermelon drizzled with  two tablespoons lemon juice, one tablespoon olive oil, and a dash of salt. Topped with fresh peppermint leaves and Westfield Capri fresh goat cheese.  #f52contest

Beautiful people! We just sold out for our House Made Cheese Supper on July 19th @61local. Please stay tuned for our next Brooklyn Backyard Bonanza, happening in August.

After a long day filled with big business decisions and summer rain, we're welcoming #nationalmacandcheeseday with open arms and empty bellies. Here's a quick parsley pecorino pesto mac and cheese with caramelized onions and garlic scapes. So green, so delicious.  #vscocam

It's popsicle week and we are super ready to celebrate. Recipe is #ontheblog!! That's right, our new website and blog is officially up (Link in profile)!

caption:
What are you doing this August? Chillin' in NYC, by chance? 
Folks, tickets are officially available for our BK Backyard Housemade Cheesy Benefit Dinner on 8/20 with @strongropebrewery. The link is in the profile! ;-) Also, that epic squash blossom #grilledcheese recipe is officially up on our journal on our website. Oh yummy day!
How about a Honeyed Mascarpone #cheesecake with strawberry coulis and a toasted  almond crust? How about it? #nationalcheesecakeday

August is all about #skewers. Here's a peek of pesto house mozzarella tomato skewers with marinated mushrooms, soon to be featured at the Bushwick  Backyard Benefit Dinner for #cityharvest #outrunhunger. It's on August 20th, link in profile!

We're all busy here in Providence,  RI, prepping for the #americancheesesociety Festival of Cheese this evening. All hands on deck and off the phone!

But one of these Wheymonade Rum Drinks would be really nice about now... This recipe yields 4 to 6 servings
1 quart cheesemaking/yogurt whey
1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
2 Tablespoons Orange Blossom Honey
3 to 6oz rum (depending on how boozy you like it)
Thinly sliced lemon for garnish

Whisk all ingredients together until well combined. Who knew drinking rum could be so delicious and nutritious?  #Whey is filled with proteins, minerals, and probiotics. #f52grams

Parmesan piquillo pepper cast iron cornbread slathered with maple butter. This recipe is studded with fresh corn kernels.  Replacing cornmeal with corn flour makes the bread lighter and more custardy. Recipe below!
Melt 1 T butter in a 9 inch cast iron skillet. Heat oven to 400 degrees F with skillet inside. 
Whisk together 1 cup cornflour, 1 cup flour, 1/2 t salt, and 2 t baking soda. 
In a separate bowl, whisk together 3/4 plain yogurt, 1/2 cup milk, and 1 egg. 
Pour into the dry ingredients and store to combine. Stir in 5 T melted butter, one chopped piquillo pepper, 1/2 cup corn kernels, and 1\2 cup grated Parm. 
Remove skillet from the oven when it has reached 400 , pour the batter evenly into the skillet, and bake for 20 to 25 minutes. Let cool 10 mins before serving. 
Serve with softened butter drizzled with maple syrup.  #f52grams #morningslikethese

caption: This is a moment where, over time, an already firmer batch of Nettle Meadow Kunik (goat cow triple cream cheese) cured slowly in the refrigerator. It has lost its characteristic creamy interior and has become something entirely different: A cheese for crumbling in a salad or over pasta. Never underestimate the shelf life of your cheese, or the flavors and textures that can emerge from one single wheel. The cheese lives and changes, and it can be enjoyed at every stage of its beautiful, fermented life.

This straightforward breakfast provides a variety of nutrients to get your day started right. The #americancheese, Atika, is an aged goat and sheep variety from @tolumafarms.  Being high in calcium and protein, goat and sheep cheese also has such important vitamins as A, D and E, which are fundamental to metabolic processes such as tissue preservation and calcium absorption. Add a brown sugar broiled grapefruit and a cup of Joe, and you've got Vitamin C and a nice buzz added to your morning.
Beautiful morning for a garden cheese photoshoot with @deleonevictoria. #thisisfall #sundayfunday

Holiday breakfast idea! Baked eggs with potatoes, mushrooms, garlic, thyme, and a deliciously melty cheese. 
3 baking potatoes, peeled and cubed
1 tbsp sunflower oil
2.5 cups mushrooms, quartered
2 garlic cloves, sliced
2 tbsp thyme leaves
1/2 cup cheddar(or other melty style), grated
4 eggs

Heat oven to 400 F. Put the potatoes in a pan of water, bring to the boil, cook for 5 mins, then drain. Heat the oil in a large frying pan. Cook the potatoes, mushrooms and garlic for 5-8 mins to soften the mushrooms and brown the edges of the potatoes. Stir in half the thyme and cook for 1 min more.
Spoon the potato mixture into a baking dish and sprinkle with the cheese and the remaining thyme. Make holes in the mixture and break in 4 eggs. Bake in the oven for 12-15 mins until the eggs are set and the cheese has melted.

New favorite natural butter churning product, inspired by Arabic traditions, at the #fooddesign conference this weekend. Description from one of the two product designers, Ottonier Roeder: ‚ÄúRachla‚Äù in arabic means ‚Äújourney‚Äù but it is also the name of a goat-leather bag which, once filled with heavy cream, was carried by the camels through the Negev desert. The constant movement of the animals produced enough energy to separate the cream into butter and buttermilk. Occasionally the leather bag was instead dangling from a wood sticks construction next to a camp tent and shaked repetetively with the arms by the women of the group. This object focuses on the spontaneous movements of our body and performs specific relationships. Walking in the countryside, climbing up a mountain, collecting heavy cream directly from the farmers. On the way home it will turn into butter.

caption:
It's time to start testing out and fine tuning our #Thanksgiving dinner recipes, adding cheese in where necessary (aka on everything). First up: this Leek and Pancetta Potato Rosti from @myrecipes, that we topped with fontina cheese. Is anyone else looking for a spin on regular potatoes?

Ingredients
4 1/2 cups shredded peeled baking potato (about 2 pounds)
3 ounces diced pancetta 
1 large leek, halved lengthwise and thinly sliced (white and light green parts only)
3 tablespoons all-purpose flour 
2 tablespoons chopped fresh sage
1/2 teaspoon kosher salt 
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper 
1 large egg 
2 tablespoons olive oil 
Preparation
1. Place shredded potato on a double layer of cheesecloth. Gather edges of cheesecloth together; squeeze cheesecloth to extract excess moisture. Place potato in a bowl.
2. Heat a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Add pancetta; cook 4 minutes or until lightly browned and crisp. Stir in leek; cook 4 minutes or until tender. Add pancetta mixture, flour, sage, salt, pepper, and egg to potato; stir well to combine.
3. Return pan to medium-high heat. Add oil; swirl to coat. Add potato mixture to pan; flatten with a spatula into an even layer. Cook 12 minutes or until bottom is golden brown. Place a large plate upside down on top of pan; invert onto plate. Carefully slide potato cake into pan, browned side up. Sprinkle with a layer of fontina cheese; cook 10 minutes or until the potato is golden brown and the cheese is melted. Place potato cake on a cutting board; cool slightly. Cut into 8 wedges.

We're really starting to dream about Thanksgiving dinner...especially this side of roasted fennel with rosemary parmesan breadcrumbs.  Ingredients:
2 tablespoons chopped walnuts 
2 (1-ounce) slices whole-grain bread, torn into pieces
2 tablespoons olive oil, divided 
2 teaspoons finely chopped fresh rosemary
4 medium fennel bulbs, trimmed and halved lengthwise (about 4 pounds)
1/4 teaspoon kosher salt 
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper 
2 tablespoons cider vinegar
1/4 cup grated parmesan. 
Preparation:
1. Preheat oven to 375¬∞.
2. Place walnuts and bread in the bowl of a mini food processor; pulse 3 to 4 times or until coarse crumbs form. Heat a large nonstick skillet over medium heat. Add 1 tablespoon oil; swirl to coat. Add rosemary; cook 30 seconds. Add nut mixture; cook 4 minutes, stirring frequently. 
3. Cut each fennel half into 4 wedges. Combine fennel, remaining 1 tablespoon oil, salt, and pepper on a foil-lined baking sheet; toss. Bake at 375¬∞ for 45 minutes or until edges are lightly browned, turning after 20 minutes. Drizzle with vinegar. Sprinkle with walnut mixture; toss to coat. Add parmesan.

Disclaimer: There's no cheese in this recipe, but Moroccan food was one of Jess' first loves, and this is a great adaptation of a whole turkey for that small gathering. The wintry flavors of orange and pomegranate brighten the turkey legs, and bring some dynamic flavors to the Thanksgiving table. 
We rubbed inside the skin of turkey legs with @vermontcreamery rich #culturedbutter, which enhanced the turkey's overall meatiness. 
Then we made this sauce for the drumsticks:

1 cup fresh orange  juice

1/4 cup brown sugar

1 T white wine vinegar

Orange Peel strips from one orange

1/2 teaspoon crushed red pepper

Pomegranate seeds

Bring juice, vinegar, and sugar to a boil, turn to low and simmer 5 minutes or until thickened, stir in crushed red pepper. Stir in orange peel and pomegranate seeds..

I believe raw milk should be accessible to everyone. Food laws should be applicable to small and medium scale production, not only applicable to large food corporation processes.
 Repost from @jasperhillfarm using @RepostRegramApp - Bayley Hazen once sat here. The world's best unpasteurized cheese is now under threat by shifting FDA regulations. Want to protect your right to eat raw milk cheese? Then please ACT this week. We need raw milk cheese lovers to call or email their Congressional representatives and tell them that our industry needs good regulation that is developed transparently and based on sound science. The deadline to comment is Monday, November 30. For more info visit www.jasperhillfarm.com/fda. #saveourcheese #rawmilkcheeseforlife

Thinking back on when I was hanging with the cool kids. 
When I was 23, I managed the French American cheese making operation at Monteillet Fromagerie in Dayton, WA.

Joan and Pierre Louis Monteillet wanted a life more socialist in nature, they saw the farm as a breeding ground for locally grown culture and community.  It was apparent that the surrounding and growing population of liberals in this remote area of the Wild West hungered for a raw and creative lifestyle, an escape from a cynical urban existence, and Joan seemed to spearhead the way with her slow food philosophy and brazen independent spirit.  I was entranced by her fearlessness in the face of a daunting capitalist regime.

This regram of Beet Kvass by @centuryfarmer has got me inspired by  natural, fresh cheese #whey once again. The snow is here and contagious colds are around every corner! Protect yourself with the healing tonic of beets, whey, water and sea salt.  Going home to do this now! #yeswhey

Ingredients:
2 medium or 1 large organic beet
1 quart-sized mason jar 
2 tbsp whey
1 tsp sea salt
filtered water

Instructions:
Peel the beets and chop into 1‚Ä≥ chunks. Place beets in the bottom of the clean mason jar. To the jar, add 1 tsp sea salt and 2 tbsp whey. Fill the jar with water up to 1‚Ä≥ below the top of the jar. Put the lid on the jar and shake well. Place the jar at room temperature for 2 days without drinking before transferring to the refrigerator for use.  Drain off the liquid, leaving the beets in the bottom of the mason jar, and enjoy as a tonic drink.

When all the liquid has been drunk, the cycle may be repeated one time by adding the same amount of whey and sea salt to the jar that now contains only beets. Re-fill the jar with water up to 1‚Ä≥ below the top of the jar. Leave at room temperature for another two days without drinking before transferring to the refrigerator for use.

It's a croque madame kinda morning. Layered with bechamel sauce and raclette and topped with a soft boiled egg.  @61localkitchen #catering

I've been crazy about goat cheese mousse...the texture and the mouth-feel.  I've been perfecting my house made recipe with black pepper and it acts as a great cheesy bed for roasted oyster mushrooms and barley risotto. This will be featured at the @drinkicd Valentine's event. Come join! #linkinbio

The Manhattan view @drinkicd is gorgeous...combine that with housemade cheeses, a seasonal feast, and expertly crafted cocktails, and you've got yourself a Valentine's celebration. Event tickets are in the bio! cheesegrotto.com/events

Ever wonder how to pair our handmade Gruyere cheese caramel with other tasty cheese board additions? We're playing with a variety of flavorful combinations, soon to be #ontheblog! caption: Wood and cheese: a match made in heaven. Natural cheese has been aged and stored on wood for centuries, as it was the only local material available. Wood's porous nature helps maintain humidity without condensation and also helps cultivate the particular ambient cultures necessary for different styles of cheeses. #cheeselove

caption: Spring is all about that green. Here's a spread of the green things that inspire this time of year, with a log of homemade cultured tarragon butter. #springforward
There are still two spots left this Saturday for the Cheese & Amaro Tasting & Tutorial in the @iforgotitswednesday Chelsea loft. It will be swanky and delicious. cheesegrotto.com/events #linkinbio

My favorite dishes for a busy work week can all be placed in one ceramic dish and popped in the oven. Satisfying roasty goodness (mushrooms and potatoes), cheddar, thyme, and baked eggs. You can find this simple recipe through the link in @thefeedfeed bio. Feedfeed.info/grownyc #eggweek

The Cheese + Amaro Tasting this Saturday is sold out ! But there is another event on the horizon that I encourage you to attend. We'll be celebrating Raw Milk Cheese Appreciation Day @61local in Brooklyn and it's going to be a delicious party. Featured in this photo is Heinennellie from @vultocreamery. cheesegrotto.com/events  #rawmilkcheese

It's a fuzzy Friday @thefarmatdoerun. Kidding season is happening, and it makes me miss the farmstead cheese making life. In the meantime, let's all enjoy the baby goat photos in their feed. Photo cred: @thefarmatdoerun #tgif

Enjoy the weekend. And please make sure to enjoy a wedge of cheese for me. How beautiful is the paste and rind of Creme de Coulee's Leopold? It is multifaceted and dimensional. #cheeselove #darlingweekend

caption: Pre-game before tonight's sold out Cheese + Amaro Tasting with @iforgotitswednesday. The Breakfast Plan! @thecastelloplan #darlingweekend

My favorite adult Easter egg hunt was back on the Monteillet Cheese Farm in 2010. Their heritage breed hens lay a rainbow of eggs, nature's dye. These chickens are so free range, that the morning egg gathering can only be called a hunt: some eggs can be found by the riverside, others can be found in every cranny of the hen house or under a pile of sticks. #happyeaster

Next up in the world of cheese celebration....Raw Milk Cheese Appreciation Day!! Save the date, April 16th and reserve your spot to our big bash through the #linkinbio. Here's a sneak peek of the dessert course: Panna Cotta with Rhubarb Berry Sorrel Syrup, Cheese Crisp, + Wedge of Dunbarton Blue. Explore your cheese palate! #f52grams @cheesecoalition

Did you know that clay is one of the original materials used by cheese makers? Clay pots would incubate and store the cheese culture that is then added to milk in the cheese making process: its porous nature preserves a cheese's signature microbial flavor and texture within its walls. Cheese Grotto uses hand fired clay for our humidity regulation in the humidor.  And it works wonderfully.

caption: Roasted fennel with rosemary pecorino breadcrumbs. One of many fanciful ideas for holiday gatherings. #whatsfordinner
After a successful first holiday season, it is time to reflect, relax, and take in nature's wonders. So looking forward to the year ahead.
Here's a #fbf to last New Year's appetizer idea: parmesan crisps with honey-whipped goat cheese and sprigs of thyme. #lifeandthyme
Ready. Set. Cheese. I'm looking forward to a year of preserving high quality cheese and agriculture, one Grotto at a time. Let's do this.
Raising a slice of @tartinebakery bread with rudolphe le meunier butter. This bread is perfection. Almost time to head back to NYC to get the Grotto game on.

Absolutely in love with this #cheeseboard by @organicliqueurs. Rich shropshire blue, bitter fresh radicchio, and a baguette introduce a wonder of flavors. Throw in a french radish or two to cleanse the palate.

Although it's almost the second week of January, I'm still reflecting on 2016, it's highs and it's lows, and it's lessons to be learned in 2017.  What I've come away with: be powerful, be strong, fight for what's right, and celebrate food and culture. Oh, and, make more cheese boards. They seem to be irresistible. #top9of2016

This evening, I was sent a dreamy picnic scene from Uruguay. This happy customer had her son travel on a plane with the Grotto. The Grotto has officially made it to jet setting, international status. Now that's some real #cheeselove.

Why make the Grotto in the United States? On the blog today: a peek into my journey to Richmond, Virginia, where the Grotto is made. The Grotto is an American-born idea, fueled by a passion and obsession for specialty cheese and everything it represents: local and regional agricultural economies, sustainable farming practices, high quality milk, humane treatment of dairy animals, and the pure joy and wonder of the subtle variety between each batch of cheese.  #linkinbio #cheeselove

caption: I'm reading Habitat by designer @laurenliess, and I've fixated on the term "juxtaposition" in design. Artisan cheese, and the Grotto, embodies many of these concepts: new vs old, rough vs smooth, light vs dark, grand vs humble. Here we have a snap from the #mindtherind campaign back last year with @culturecheese. A clothbound cheddar rind up-close conveys a myriad of textures and sensations. Photo by @sarahecrowder.

More #cheesemeditation #ontheblog today: a #mindtherind photo journal with @sarahecrowder. Look deep into the #cheeserind. What do you see? Featured in this photo is the rind of Corsu Vecchiu, a Corsican sheep milk cheese. #linkinbio ‚ô°
Here's a #tbt to our trip to Virginia. Stephan, the skilled carpenter, assembles and finishes each Grotto before they are shipped. You can read more #ontheblog. ‚ô° #makersgonnamake
#tgif Now this, on repeat, please.

Don't miss out! Through the month of February, #cheesegrotto owners get $50 towards @saxelbycheese of the month clubs when they purchase a Grotto! What could be a better combo? Saxelby is the retail leader in American artisan cheese, and they are pioneers of the industry. #cheeselove
Cheesy crisps, anyone? #Oscars appetizer ideas for tonight can be found on @thefeedfeed cheese page, edited by me (follow the link in their bio!). This recipe featured is by @snixykitchen. ‚ô°
@ediblebrooklyn loved our #mindtherind campaign so much, they asked us to do a takeover on their feed. All this week! Rinds and cheese musings! What else could you want?
The @ediblebrooklyn #mindtherind takeover continues, this time it's Pawlet from @considerbardwell.  Look at that basket weave on that cheese rind! Photo @sarahecrowder

I keep saying "Happy Spring!" to people today, but it really isn't, it's just warm out. Nevertheless, I'm impatiently waiting to decorate cheese in edible flowers because it tastes, smells, and looks nice. ‚ô°‚ô°‚ô° #humpday

More from the @ediblebrooklyn #mindtherind takeover:
Like an oil painting, thickly painted with numerous layers and colors, the Maxorata Pimenton #cheeserind is a vibrant thing to see. This aged goat cheese is rolled in paprika and becomes dappled with molds as it ages, creating some vibrant contrasts. It is an ivory-yellow cheese on the inside¬†with slightly sweet, spicy and toasted flavors, dense and creamy at the same time. 
Photo by @sarahecrowder

Almost time for this again...this is still one of my favorite shots from a spring homemade cheese dinner I cooked over a year ago. I could stare at these vibrant colors and homemade tarragon butter for days.

caption: Sunday stretch.

Recently, I've been reflecting a lot on WHY I invented and developed the Cheese Grotto. I've poured all my energy over the past couple of years into this little thing of beauty. And it really comes down to my passion for the specialty cheese movement. Specialty cheese changed my life for the better: the community, the land values, and the authenticity of its devotees. It sparked a culinary adventure, and now I'm eleven years deep. More to come #ontheblog this week, but my interview with @misscheesemonger on her blog captures part of the story.

Photo cred @misscheesemonger

"The notion of #cheeseterroir is not solely a turophile's indulgence. At its heart, it is not about snobbery or elitism. Rather, it is about local agricultural economies that sustain themselves from ecologically sound practices of land and animal management. This can power an entire regional economy for hundreds of years." Hit the #linkinbio to read more on the Cheese Grotto Philosophy and Methodology. ‚ô°‚ô°‚ô°

From the inimitable cheese expert Steven Jenkins on storing cheese in the Cheese Grotto at room temperature: "Soft-ripened cheeses, middle-aged chevres, mountain cheeses, blue cheeses -- all are properly cosseted by the Grotto in the manner they deserve. Fine cheese that you have spent a lot of money on should be brought home and consumed over a period ¬†of days -- not weeks. That's only fair to that particular cheese. Wrapped, refrigerated cheeses hanging around for more than a week are stale cheeses. Buy smaller portions. Knock them off. Go back to¬†[the cheese shop]¬†more often. Keep them in your gorgeous grotto, and keep it nearby." Truly poetic. Hit the #linkinbio to read more about keeping your cheese on the kitchen counter, like the French do.

caption: Have you ever had black market cheese? What if that was the only way you could make a local food product? That's what Spanish artisan cheese makers did under Franco's rule. If it is the choice to have local community and independent food systems, I believe that I, too, would do whatever it takes to keep our food system diverse: for the future of food and nourishment. Why don't we start making decisions with our values, and what we want to see in the world? As Slow Money Investors say, "with food, everyone is an investor." Boy, isn't it true that our every day decisions affect the community that directly surrounds us. Buy local, think regional is what I say. The world is made of food traditions that are a source of pride and global deliciousness. That's how I like to view the world. #mindtherind

Oh, hello world! After the wild holiday months, and the snowy blanket that fell in NYC, I took a small break from social media. I cleared my head, and focused on my life, with and without cheese. The consensus remains: life, especially in the winter, is better with cheese. This quick cast-iron #fondue with roasted potatoes and brussel sprouts is one of the best ways to melt down what's left in your Grotto at home. Recipe #linkinbio ‚ùÑüî•üßÄüî•‚ùÑ
Photo @direwolfandco

Cut through the cold with bright, smoky, briney, piquant, and rich Monte Enebro Spanish goat cheese. Monte Enebro was invented around 25 years ago and is a flagship of the artisan cheese movement in Spain. Its exterior is ripened with a layer of penicillium roqueforti, the same mold used to make Roquefort Blue Cheese. The signature blue flavor does not penetrate the cheese, but it does add to its overall complexity and intense flavor profile as it ripens. Pair it well with Gewurztraminer, Sauternes, or Muscat tonight.

Cheese is just as addictive as chocolate, if not more. Did you know that cheese contains an amino acid called tyrosine which increases dopamine, the neurotransmitter responsible for making you happy? Tyrosine can be found in bountiful amounts in aged cheeses in the form of those crunchy crystals we all know and love (think Parmigiano Reggiano and super-aged Goudas). In fact, cheese has the potential to exceed chocolate as the signature pick-me-up.  So get your lover a Grotto and one of our cheese packages this Valentine's Day. üßÄ‚ù§üßÄ üì∏ @direwolfandco

Since we'll be celebrating #rawmilkcheeseday tomorrow evening, I thought it a perfect time to discuss #naturalwine with my friend and wine expert @giannoniselections on the Cheese Grotto blog. Natural wine is similar to raw milk cheese in its  focus on the terrain, climate, and grape in order to make the wine shine. Raw milk cheese also focuses on the land, the feed, the milk, and the climate to make the best cheese possible. Both mediums avoid the use of other controls in the make process such as sulfur or heat treatment, to bring out a beautifully balanced taste of place. Where's the beef... and cheese? From cured to grilled, sausage is a fatty bold meat flecked with spices, herbs, and salt.  We recommend robust cheeses to pair with this robust food. 
A clothbound farmhouse cheddar such as Jasper Hill Farm's Cabot Clothbound is full of dynamic flavor: ranging from grassy to caramel-y to brothy: it makes a wonderfully dynamic pairing with grilled or pan-fried italian sausages. 
For cured Finocchiona (fennel-studded) sausage, we recommend the creamy, tangy, and earthy Jasper Hill Farm Landaff cheese.  Tie it all together with a glass of whisky and a multi-grain mustard. 
Go bolder with a blue cheese or washed rind when pairing with a smokier or spicier cured meat.  Give into cheese, sausage, and more this Father's Day

As summer becomes more lush, green, and floral, so does the flavor of high quality cheese. From fresh to aged, farmstead cheeses are made with milk from dairy animals who are allowed to graze and forage on diverse plots of land. Their milk reflects a taste of place. Featured in this photo is Twig Farm Goat Tomme, produced out of the diverse pastures of West Cornwall, VT.

When I started my company in November 2016, I didn't completely realize the grand undertaking of launching an inventive product. I was consumed by my passion for specialty cheese, and I wanted to share my creation with the world.¬† As I continued to develop the Cheese Grotto concept, I realized that I was innovating within the world of dairy: on both a product and business level.¬† The knowledge I have gained from starting my own innovative food business has been inherently valuable.¬† Please join me at @strongropebrewery tomorrow night at 6pm, for a candid conversation about #designthinking with @businessmodelsinc and @strongropebrewery.¬† There will be a Cheese Grotto pop up store, beer, and tasty treats like my @cheesecaramels. caption: Soak up those warm summer nights while you still can. Here's a fall back Friday to a backyard cheese dinner to remember. An oldie, but a goodie. The first time I immersed myself in specialty cheese @cowgirlcreamery when I worked at their counter, I was hooked. I was hooked to the variety of flavors and textures that could come from the same cheese in different seasons. I was hooked to the tyrosine that lifted my mood. I was hooked to the community around me that celebrated and worked for quality food each and every day. That is the origin story of Cheese Grotto: 12 years ago as a wild and goofy 19 year old, just loving what the industry was feeding me. Literally. #lifebeginsaftercheese

Back in the magical city of Montr√©al where I will subsist off of les fromages du Qu√©bec for one whole week. Here we have Le Pleine Lune by Fromagerie 1860 Duvillage. It's an ash-ripened cow milk cheese enriched with cream that won  the title of Best Canadian cheese in the 2016 World Cheese Awards.

Back from Montr√©al, and fall feels like it is officially here. There are many exciting updates that I can't wait to share with you, but for now, we must keep them a secret. üòé Qu√©bec is a specialty cheese haven, and we're looking forward to working more with our friends across the border: all in the name of giving cheese lovers the best experience they can have with friends, family, and colleagues. caption: People often ask, "But can you store cuts of different styles of cheese in the Cheese Grotto at the same time?" The answer is YES. caption: Sheep milk cheeses are exceptionally fatty and delicious. From soft and spreadable to dense and salty, sheep milk cheese has its own characteristics, textures, and flavor profiles. This @vermontshepherd cheese called Queso del Invierno is a dense sheep cheese aged during the winter months. I've shared some of my sheep milk insights through the #linkinbio if you'd like to learn more. I had the honor to work closely with sheep and their milk during my time at The Monteillet Fromagerie in Dayton, Washington and sheep cheese became an obsession...

This Valentine's Day, surprise your lover with some delicious cheese, and get creative with the board display. These cheese collages reflect the flavors & aromas of these @jasperhillfarm cheeses. These are also great pairings for the cheeses! Featuring: Willoughby (washed rind), Weybridge (lactic bloomy rind) & Harbison (rich spruce bark wrapped bloomy rind), all available in our Preserve the Curd package.

I often reflect on the quality of our products and the values they represent -- sustainable, long-lasting, Made in NY, attention to detail, excellent customer service, and small-batch production. As our company grows, I don't want to compromise our integrity. But I do want cheese lovers everywhere to be able to access a Cheese Grotto if they identify with our brand and values. Perhaps you'll be surprised to know our prices are not inflated -- they are built off of a sound business model that lets us to grow honestly and with integrity.
That's why I am excited to partner with Klarna, a payment option now on our site that allows our customers to Slice payments into 4 stages. Now you can purchase items at $100 or more over 8 weeks from purchase date -- which will be easier on your bank account and will help us preserve our production process & values. Simply chose Klarna at checkout.
A win-win!
Please let me know if you have any questions about this payment option, I'm happy to assist.
Sincerely, Jessica, Founder of Cheese Grotto.

Counter or fridge? Fridge or counter? The question we get the most about the Cheese Grotto is where to store it. And the answer is....BOTH! Our Grotto models are designed to fit well in a small to large refrigerator as well as sit nicely on the kitchen counter. Many of our customers store the Grotto in the fridge so they can hold onto cheese for months, but if you frequent the cheese shop often and enjoy your cheese within 7 to 10 days, the Grotto can stay on the counter -- to be enjoyed like the French do. The temperature requirement is that the cheese stay under 70 degrees F -- your cheese will ripen faster at room temperature so be sure to check-in every couple of days especially with those softer styles that ripen more quickly. Please let us know if you have further questions!! Each Grotto comes with a nice booklet on the subject for the real cheese obsessives among us. üòé

Finally -- we have a limited run of Classico Black Boards available. Sold independently or with the Classico, these black boards are unbreakable, dishwasher safe, NSF certified, and you can write on them with the included soapstone chalk piece. Pre-order now, there are only 19 left currently....!

caption: I've been thinking a lot about slow living this weekend. What a practice to counteract the hustle and bustle, the era of overstimulation in which we live. Specialty cheese represents more to me than a premium food item - it is something that embraces the heritage and tradition of slow food practices which sustain us from the land underneath our feet. Cheesemaking, a process that is step by step, methodical and meditative in nature, and a natural phenomenon of transformation. It's part of my obsession with the earth and it's beautiful living force. caption: "Pleasant Ridge Reserve is an interpretation of alpine-style cheeses like Beaufort and Gruyere, which for hundreds of years have been made with the summer, grass-fed milk.¬† So the style of cheese was really just an extension of the style of milk we were producing.¬† This sounds logical but I think it's actually pretty rare in cheesemaking.¬† More often cheeses are invented with marketing as the primary driver, not the character of the raw material." Click the link in bio to learn more about the great cheesemaker, Andy Hatch, who is behind the iconic Wisoncin Pleasant Ridge Reserve and Rush Creek. üì∏ @uplandscheese

üêê French Bouche Goat Cheese is a dense, creamy bloomy rind style that tastes lemony, mineral, and like white button mushrooms. ‚Å£
üçÑ Its texture is similar to a fresh goat cheese, but the few weeks age and bloomy rind development make it more dense, complex, and earthy.‚Å£
üòõ And just look at that cream-line.

üêê@nettle_meadow_farm Kunik is a triple cream, mixed milk bloomy rind style cheese that is often spreadable and creamy. ‚Å£
üá´üá∑ Like a French crottin, this cheese can become denser when left forgotten in the back of the refrigerator wrapped in a breathable cheese paper for a couple weeks. ‚Å£
üí™Embrace the difference! ‚Å£
üßÄ Cheese is a living, breathing thing and can be enjoyed at varying textures and flavors.  That variety is what makes artisan cheese so distinct from its machine-made counterparts.

üçì Preheat oven to 375 F. Beat 1/4 cup sugar, 1 egg, 1/2 teaspoon vanilla and 3/4 cup cr√®me fra√Æche in bowl until well blended.‚Å£
üçì Fill 4 4oz ramekins with custard, top with fresh raspberries. Place ramekins in a baking dish filled with water that reaches halfway up the ramekins.‚Å£
üçì Bake for 20 minutes, or until custard is set.  Allow to cool for 45 minutes, then enjoy!
